Japan, Indonesia, South Korea, Philippines: Asian Bonds, Currency Preview

-- B y   K h a l i d   Q a y u m
-- 
2011-05-01T22:20:51Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-01/japan-indonesia-south-korea-philippines-asian-bonds-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in  Asia ’s bonds and currencies
today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the previous
trading session unless stated otherwise.  Financial markets in Singapore, Malaysia,  Thailand , and
 China  are closed today for a holiday.  Japan : Chief Cabinet Secretary Yukio Edano will hold a
regular press conference.  The Ministry of Health, Labor and Welfare will release its
report on labor cash earnings for March. Salaries in February
rose 0.3 percent from a year earlier.  The yield on the 1.3 percent government bond due March 2021
was 1.2 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker. The yen traded at
81.18 per dollar at 7:18 a.m. in  Tokyo .  India : The commerce ministry will release data on exports
for March. Overseas shipments in February increased 49.7 percent
from a year earlier.  The yield on the 7.8 percent bond due April 2021 was 8.13
percent. The rupee was at 44.215 per dollar.  Indonesia: Consumer prices rose 6.4 percent in April from a
year earlier, after increasing 6.65 percent in March, according
to the median forecast of economists before official data.  Exports increased 25.3 percent in March, from a gain of
28.9 percent the previous month, another survey showed before
data to be released by the statistics department.  The yield on the 8.25 percent bond due July 2021 was 7.8
percent. The rupiah was at 8,570 per dollar.  South Korea : Consumer prices rose 4.6 percent in April from
a year earlier, after gaining 4.7 percent the previous month,
according to the median forecast in a Bloomberg survey before
official data today.  The government will sell 1.5 trillion won ($1.4 billion) of
three-year bonds.  The yield on South Korea’s 3 percent bond due December 2013
was 3.77 percent. The won was at 1,071.53 per dollar.  Philippines: The government will sell 9 billion pesos ($210
million) of 91-, 182- and 364-day bills.  The yield on the 7.375 percent bond due March 2021 was 6.1
percent, according to Tradition Financial Services. The peso was
at 42.845 per dollar.  Thailand: Consumer prices rose 3.2 percent in April from a
year earlier after increasing 3.14 percent the previous month,
according to the median forecast of economists in a Bloomberg
survey before a report today.  The yield on the 3.125 percent debt due December 2015 was
3.33 percent. The baht was at 29.93 per dollar.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Khalid Qayum in  Singapore  at 
 kqayum@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
